# Firebase & Firestore Patterns

## Firestore Schema
```
invites/{inviteId}
  ├── hostId, location, dateTime, heading, hostName, templateType, createdAt
  ├── gifts/{giftId}     — itemName, link, isClaimed, claimedBy
  └── rsvps/{rsvpId}     — guestName, pax, timestamp
users/{uid}              — uid, email
```

## Avoiding Composite Index Errors
Firestore requires composite indexes for `where()` + `orderBy()` on different fields. To avoid forcing users to create indexes, sort client-side instead:

```ts
// ❌ Requires composite index
query(collection(db, "invites"), where("hostId", "==", uid), orderBy("createdAt", "desc"))

// ✅ Filter in Firestore, sort in JS
const snap = await getDocs(query(collection(db, "invites"), where("hostId", "==", uid)));
return results.sort((a, b) => b.createdAt.getTime() - a.createdAt.getTime());
```

## Gift Claiming — Use Transactions
When guests claim gifts, use `runTransaction` to atomically check `isClaimed === false` and then set it to `true`. This prevents two guests from claiming the same gift.

## Auth Pattern
Auth state is managed via `AuthProvider` in `src/lib/auth-context.tsx`. Use `useAuth()` hook in client components. Dashboard routes check `user` state and redirect to `/` if null.
